Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrdvrsc] <silkspinner> @DaveArcher  Block height is simply the length of the Verus chain , the total number of blocks . Hash rate is a measurement of mining activity, basically one guess at winning a block. The hash rate of your miners can be compared to the total network hash rate to estimate the likelihood of your winning a particular block. See FAQ for how to do that calculation.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content:
[dscrdvrsc] <bigtom> This really is going to have an effect on the software industry in California and freelance/contract workers:
https://klasing-associates.com/california-changes-employer-rules/

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrdvrsc] <jimboscott> @bigtom I have had to deal with these kinds of things myself.  Reclassifying contractor/employee relationships is tricky.  It puts the burden for taxation on the employer, but the rules governing intellectual property will probably also be skewed in the employer's favor as any work output from an employee is generally automatically considered the intellectual property of the employer.  I am a professional photographer. As long as I am independent, copyright laws automatically protect me.  If I was classified as a photographer AND an employee I do not have a leg to stand on.  Would not surprise me if the software industry was not cheering this on in secret....

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrdvrsc] <jimboscott> Independent contractors would address intellectual property concerns through contracts.  There, the contractor has some room for negotiation.  Not so if an employee.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrdvrsc] <bigtom> Often photographs and code are works for hire. If you get paid to produce the photos the client owns the photos and at least share the copyright.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrdvrsc] <bigtom> Works for hire in software often have specific contracts about ownership and copyright.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrdvrsc] <bigtom> I was looking at the part of it where companies have to. Over all the employment costs they used to avoid. Have an actual employee give more obvious ownership of work product.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content:
[dscrdvrsc] <wistar> @Scrotum Tickler: I've had this happen. Are the connection counts the same?

Are they networked via WiFi or ethernet/hard-wired? If the latter, try switching connections between the two and see if the slow hash follows.

Either WiFi or ethernet: You can try:
```ipconfig /release
ipconfig /renew```
to get a new lease and see if that is the culprit.

Finally, try stopping Agama on the slow laptop, let it exit completely, shut the machine down (rather than just re-starting), start the machine and than try loading and running Agama again. This has usually worked for me.
